iting Culture era. They address questions of ethnographic method, new forms the presentation of research might take, and the anthropologist's role. Exploring themes such as late industrialism, precarity, violence, science and technology, globalization, and the non-human world, this book is essential reading for those looking to understand the current state of anthropology and its possibilities going forward.Contributors. Anne Allison, James Clifford, Michael M.J. Fischer, Kim Fortun, Richard Handler, John L. Jackson, Jr., George E. Marcus, Charles Piot, Hugh Raffles, Danilyn Rutherford, Orin Starn, Kathleen Stewart, Michael Taussig, Kamala Visweswaran  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 12. Dez 2020) 0aAnthropologyxAuthorship. 0aCommunication in ethnology. 0aEthnologyxAuthorship. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Anthropology / Cultural & Social.2bisacsh1 aAllison, Anne, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aPiot, Charles, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aRutherford, Danilyn, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMarcus, George E., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aRaffles, Hugh, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aClifford, James, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aJackson Jr, John L., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aVisweswaran, Kamala, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aStewart, Kathleen, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFortun, Kim, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFischer, Michael M. J., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aTaussig, Michael, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/